node.text:
The earliest record of cheddar anywhere is at Cheddar, in Somerset, in 1170. The land around this village has been at the heart of English cheesemaking since the 15th century. Today, as many Cheddar producers have upscaled and require more land, there is only one traditional cheesemaker in the village.

#cheddar #cheese #charcuterieboard #cheesemaking #foodofinstagram

node.title: Why traditional English cheddar is aged in caves | Regional Eats

It’s harder to achieve the perfect chocolate chip cookie than you might think. From too much butter to not enough flour to confusing baking soda for baking powder, Insider’s Lisa Paradise (@lisaparadise) made 11 batches of cookie dough to try every single common cookie mistake and find out how each one affects your final bake.

#baking #chocolatechipcookies #cookies #pastry #cookierecipe #bestcookies

node.text:
If there were a competition for the most beautiful cheese, Cornish Yarg would claim the title. Each cheese is wrapped in wild stinging nettles, which are brushed on by hand one by one. With aging, the nettles form a natural rind around the cheese, giving it a fresh, creamy taste with hints of herbs, mushrooms, seaweed, and even lemon. So how did this recipe even come about? It was actually found randomly in a book about 400 years ago. We visited Lynher Dairies in the heart of Cornwall to find out more.

#cornishyarg #cheese #dairy #cornwall

node.text:
Bury, Lancashire, England is know for being the capital of black pudding. The sausage made of cereals and blood is a delicacy here, eaten as a takeaway food with sauce or in a bread roll. Richard Morris from the Bury Black Pudding Company takes us through the making process step by step. His grandfather was a butcher, and it is his black pudding recipe that the company uses today.

Featuring @clacly22

Popcorn is Illinois' official snack food, and @garrettpopcorn has been serving some of the best handcrafted popcorn in the state since 1949. The secret family recipe that's been handed down over three generations is still made in old-fashioned copper kettles with kernels that are grown just for the company. Garrett's handcrafts its popcorn in small batches throughout the day and can make anywhere from 30 to 150 batches daily. The famous Garrett mix consists of a mix of its CheeseCorn and CaramelCrisp flavors, creating a perfect blend of savory and sweet. There's almost always a line at all Garrett Popcorn shops, so Insider's Medha Imam (@medhapedia) visited one to see how the iconic mix is made and why it's one of Oprah's "Favorite Things." 

Editor's Note: Insider visited Garrett Popcorn in March 2020, before Chicago restaurants closed to dine-in service. You can still order popcorn and more for pickup and delivery. For more information, visit: www.garrettpopcorn.com

Insider's Claudia Romeo (@clacly22) traveled to Seine-et-Marne, France to visit Ferme des 30 Arpents. The farm is one of seven farms making raw-milk Brie de Meaux cheese, and the only one that makes it fermier, which means that the cheese is made by hand solely with milk produced by the 250 cows at the farm. Every day, Ferme des 30 Arpents will make about 300 wheels of Brie de Meaux from its herd's milk.

Editor's note: This footage was filmed on February 14, 2020. At present, Ferme des 30 Arpents has implemented preventive measures to ensure everyone's safety and has adopted the health regulations in force for its production of farmhouse cheeses.

The earliest record of cheddar anywhere is at Cheddar, in Somerset, in 1170. The land around this village has been at the heart of English cheesemaking since the 15th century. Today, as many Cheddar producers have upscaled and require more land, there is only one traditional cheesemaker in the village.

Durian’s smell is famously divisive. But in Asia and the Pacific Islands, durian is known as the “King of Fruit.” Nonthaburi, Thailand, is known for cultivating some of the most sought-after durian varieties: Kan Yao and Mon Thong. In 2019, one Nonthaburi, or Nont, durian sold at auction for $48,000. So, what makes this pungent, spiky fruit so expensive?

node.text:
Cake pops are a versatile, hand-held dessert made from cake, frosting, and a candy or chocolate coating. The key to making them is finding the ideal ratio of cake to frosting.

Insider broke down the steps to get the perfect cake pops for any occasion.

Click the link in our bio for the full recipe, decoration ideas, troubleshooting, and more.

(Credit: Getty Images)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo of a bundle of cake pops with the headline, "How to make delicious and customizable cake pops at home."

Photo of cake pops being dipped in chocolate with the text, "Cake pops are a convenient, bite-sized way to enjoy cake and frosting, no plates or utensils required. They have three main components — cake, frosting, and coating — which can each be customized to meet a variety of flavor profiles."

Text graphic with the list, "Ingredients: 1 full cake, any flavor; 1/2 cup frosting, any flavor; 1 bag candy melts any color," and the list, "What else you need: Lollipop sticks, cookie dough scoop, baking sheet, parchment paper."

Text graphic with the heading, "How to make cake pops," and the text, "1. Bake your cake. Allow it to fully cool. 2. Crumble the cake. Produce a fine crumb, then put the crumbs in a mixing bowl. 3. Mix cake crumbs with frosting. Add small amounts of frosting. Once you're able to form a ball with the mixture and it holds together, your mixture is ready. 4. Form cake balls. Roll and shape the balls, then place them on a baking sheet lined with parchment paper."

Text graphic with the heading, "How to make cake pops," and the text, "5. Melt the candy melts. Microwave for one minute and stir, then continue microwaving for 15-second intervals until the candy coating is melted and smooth. 6. Dip the lollipop sticks. Dip the end of a lollipop stick into the melted coating and insert the stick into the cake ball. Be sure it doesn't go through past the center. This acts like glue to keep the cake ball on the stick."

Text graphic with the heading, "How to make cake pops," and the text, "7. Freeze the cake balls. Place the baking sheet in the freezer for 15 minutes to let the cake balls chill and to allow the sticks to set. 8. Dip the cake pops. Swirl each cake pop into the candy melt coating to fully cover it. 9. Decorate and let dry. While the coating is still wet, add sprinkles or other decorations. Prop up the cake pops on a cardboard box or stand and allow them to set and harden for at least 45 minutes."

If there were a competition for the most beautiful cheese, Cornish Yarg would claim the title. Each cheese is wrapped in wild stinging nettles, which are brushed on by hand one by one. With aging, the nettles form a natural rind around the cheese, giving it a fresh, creamy taste with hints of herbs, mushrooms, seaweed, and even lemon. So how did this recipe even come about? It was actually found randomly in a book about 400 years ago. We visited Lynher Dairies in the heart of Cornwall to find out more.

node.text:
Jeff Simonian, president of Simonian Fruit Company, likes to enjoy pomegranate arils in champagne, on top of a salad, or in Jell-O. Look for pomegranates that are bright in color and heavy for their size to ensure juicy seeds. Score the peel to divide the fruit into quarters before pulling it apart with your hands. In a bowl of water, separate the arils (or seeds) from the white, inedible pith.

Click the link in our bio to read more.

(Credit: runner of art/Getty Images, Göksel Kaya / EyeEm/Getty Images)
#Pomegranate #Fruits #HowTo

node.accessibility_caption: Photo showing pomegranates with headline, "How to cut a pomegranate to get to the juicy seeds without making a mess"

Photo showing pomegranate peeling with text, "Cut off the crown: The fruit has a small, pointy protrusion on one end that looks like a crown. Use a sharp knife to slice off the crown along with a little of the white 
pith underneath."

Photo showing pomegranate peeling with text, "Slice into sections: Run a knife from the crown end all the way around the pomegranate, scoring the skin without slicing into the fruit and dividing into half. If you notice little ridges running down the length of your pomegranate, cut along those ridges. Repeat, dividing into quarters."
Photo showing pomegranate peeling with text, "Break apart: Grab each side with your hands and gently but firmly break in half along the scored lines. Break each half into quarters."

Photo showing pomegranate peeling with text, "Remove the arils: Simonian recommends placing the sections in a bowl of water and using your fingers to roll out the arils, separating them from the pith, which will float. You can also hold a section over a bowl, arils facing out, and whack the peel with a wooden spoon to dislodge the edible fruit. If you use this method, you will likely need to use your fingers to retrieve some more stubborn arils."
Photo showing pomegranate peeling with text, "Discard the peel and pith: The peel and white pith are inedible and should be tossed after retrieving the arils."

Richard Morris from the Bury Black Pudding Company takes us through the making process step by step. His grandfather was a butcher, and it is his black pudding recipe that the company uses today.
